      "The Stinson A was placed in scheduled passenger service\nby American Airlines in April, 1935. In September, 1937\nthese aircraft were withdrawn and the fleet standardized -\nusing only DC-2's and DC-3's.\nThe Stinson A was first built in 1933 - being designed\nfor eight passengers and a bostosa. for short hauls and as\na \"feeder\" for through schedules.\nThe firat version used by\nAmerican Airlines had only one pilot and carried a steward.\nThese airoralt were later modified by including a co-pilot's\nposition.\nSpen:\n60%\nLengths\n36'10•\nHeights 11'6\"\nWing Area: 535.5 sq. It.\nWing Loading:\n20.24 sq.It.\nGrosa Weight:\nEmpty Weight:\n10,1004\nPayload: 1,860#\nUseful Load:\nCrew: 2\nPassengers: 8\nEngine:\n(3) Lycoming 680-5\nTakeoff HoP.:\n260 (ea.)\nPower Loading:\nFuel Capacity:\n13#\n160 gal.\nHigh Speed: 181\nCruising Speed:\n161\nStall Speed:\n63 mph\nService Ceiling:\n17,500\nCost:\n$37,500\n• AA •\nPhoto #3505"
